Hmmm thanks for the feedback @susanu . You make a good point. At first I wanted to say "_you can't do that with `linkTo()`, you should do that with `wrapper()`_" but... it's kind of limiting then, isn't it? Passing parameters is indeed something that will be needed, soon. So why doesn't `linkTo()` offer it?

Then I realized... maybe we've been looking at this function the wrong way all this time. **If the only thing `linkTo()` does is that it binds that column to a route... then why is the syntax not similar to Laravel's `route()` helper? Why is the second parameter `target` instead of being `parameters`?** 

@pxpm what do you think if we 
- change the second parameter from the target to optional parameters (that we just pass to the `route()` call in addition to the ID we add ourselves if it exists);
- move the definition of Target from a parameter to a different macro, `linkTarget()`;

Then you could do:
```php
CRUD::column('users_count')->type('text')->linkTo('users.index', ['role' => 'smth'])->linkTarget('_blank');
```

It will still not solve @susanu 's problem 100%. Turns out @susanu you really _cannot_ do that using `routeTo()` because in your example you're using `$entry->getKey()` which you can only get by using the closure. Buut. I think the above _would_ be helpful in other cases where the parameter can be hardcoded. And it's more intuitive.

What do you think @pxpm ?

```php
// easiest use case stays the same
CRUD::column('category')->linkTo('users.index');

// custom target
CRUD::column('category')->linkTo('users.index', '_blank'); // vs
CRUD::column('category')->linkTo('users.index')->linkTarget('_blank');

// custom target and custom parameters
CRUD::column('category')->linkTo('users.index', ['smth' => 'else'])->linkTarget('_blank');
```

What do you think @pxpm ? Questions for you:

(1) Yay/nay on moving the target to a different `linkTarget()` macro?
(2) Yay/nay on making the second parameter of this function `$parameters`?

